  "prompt": "Are ductile metals also malleable?",
  "response": "Yes, ductile metals are also malleable. Both ductility and malleability are properties that describe a metal's ability to deform under stress, but they refer to different types of deformation:\n\n- **Ductility** refers to a metal's ability to be stretched into a wire or elongated without breaking. A ductile material can undergo significant plastic deformation under tensile stress.\n\n- **Malleability** refers to a metal's ability to be hammered, rolled, or pressed into thin sheets without cracking or breaking. A malleable material can undergo significant plastic deformation under compressive stress.\n\nMost metals that are ductile are also malleable because both properties involve the movement of dislocations within the metal's crystal structure, allowing the material to deform plastically. Examples of metals that are both ductile and malleable include gold, silver, aluminum, and copper.",
